const SEARCH_INDEX = {"day1":"🏠 home › day 1 — introduction to www 📅 day 01 · beginner introduction to www how does the web work? browsers, servers, http, dns, urls and the history of the internet. 🌐 📋 topics covered today what is the world wide web (www)? internet vs the web — key difference brief history of the internet and the web what is a web browser? what is a web server? how browsers and servers communicate (client-server model) what is http / https? http request and response cycle common http status codes what is dns? understanding urls and domain names types of websites — static vs dynamic 🌍 what is the world wide web? the world wide web (www) , commonly called \"the web,\" is a system of interlinked hypertext documents and multimedia content that is accessed via the internet using web browsers. it was invented by sir tim berners-lee in 1989 while he was working at cern (the european physics lab in switzerland). the web is built on three core technologies that tim berners-lee defined: html — hypertext markup language, for creating web pages http — hypertext transfer protocol, for transferring pages across the internet url — uniform resource locator, for addressing pages (web addresses) 💡 internet ≠ world wide web! the internet is the global physical network of computers connected together (the infrastructure — like roads). the web is just one service that runs on top of the internet (like cars on those roads). email, ftp, and streaming services are also separate services that use the internet. key historical milestones year event 1969 arpanet (precursor to the internet) launched by the us department of defense 1983 tcp/ip protocol adopted — this is the foundation the modern internet still uses 1989 tim berners-lee proposes the world wide web at cern 1991 the first ever website goes live at 1993 the mosaic browser makes the web graphical and accessible to everyone 1994 w3c (world wide web consortium) founded to standardize web technologies 1995 javascript invented by brendan eich; web boom begins 2004 web 2.0 era begins — interactive websites, social media, user-generated content 🖥️ web browsers and web servers what is a web browser? a web browser is a software application installed on your computer or phone that lets you access and view web pages. the browser requests pages from servers, receives the html/css/js files, and renders (draws) the final visual page you see on screen. 🌐 google chrome — most popular (uses blink engine) 🦊 mozilla firefox — open-source, privacy-focused (uses gecko engine) 🧭 safari — default on apple devices (uses webkit engine) 🌊 microsoft edge — modern windows browser 🎭 opera — built-in vpn and ad-blocker what is a web server? a web server is a computer that stores website files and \"serves\" them to browsers when requested. it runs server software (like apache or nginx ) that listens for incoming browser requests and responds with the appropriate files. stores html, css, javascript, images, databases runs 24/7 to respond to requests from anywhere in the world has a unique ip address so browsers can find it ✅ client vs server: your computer/phone is the client — it requests pages. the remote computer storing the website is the server — it responds with data. this is called the client-server model and it is the foundation of how the web works. 🔄 http & https — how browsers and servers communicate http (hypertext transfer protocol) is the set of rules that defines how web browsers and web servers communicate. think of it as the \"language\" they both agree to use when exchanging data. the http request-response cycle every time you load a webpage, this sequence happens: http — request / response cycle 📋 copy common http methods method use request a page or resource from the server (most common) submit data to the server (forms, logins) update an existing resource on the server delete a resource on the server common http status codes code meaning request succeeded — page found and returned resource has been moved to a new url permanently the request was malformed or invalid authentication is required to access this resource you don't have permission to access this resource the requested page or file does not exist something went wrong on the server's side http vs https https is the secure version of http. it wraps all communication in ssl/tls encryption , meaning that even if someone intercepts the traffic between you and the server, they see only scrambled, unreadable data. 🔒 always look for the padlock 🔒 in your browser's address bar. it confirms the site is using https and your connection to it is encrypted. never enter passwords or card details on http-only sites. 📒 dns — domain name system computers on the internet communicate using ip addresses (e.g. ), but humans prefer readable names like . the dns (domain name system) acts like the internet's phone book — it translates human-friendly domain names into ip addresses that computers can route to. how dns works: you type in your browser your browser checks its local cache — has it visited this site before? if not, it asks your isp's dns resolver for the ip address the dns resolver queries the hierarchy of dns servers until it finds the answer the ip address ( ) is returned to your browser your browser connects directly to that ip and requests the page 💡 dns is like a phone book: you look up \"google\" (the name) and it gives you their phone number (the ip address). without dns, you'd need to memorise the ip addresses of every website you want to visit! 🔗 understanding urls and domain names a url (uniform resource locator) is the full web address used to locate a specific resource on the internet. every url has distinct parts, each with a specific role. url anatomy 📋 copy breaking down the domain name part example description subdomain optional prefix; \"www\" is the most common second-level domain the unique name registered by the owner top-level domain (tld) category: .com (commercial), .org (non-profit), .edu (education), .in (india) path points to a specific page or file on the server ⚡ static vs dynamic websites not all websites work the same way. they fall into two broad categories based on how their content is generated and served. static website dynamic website content fixed — same for every visitor changes based on user, time, data technologies html, css, javascript only html + server language (php, node.js) + database speed faster (no processing needed) slower (server must generate content) examples portfolio, landing pages, documentation gmail, facebook, amazon, youtube in this course ✅ days 1–14 (html, css, bootstrap) ✅ days 15+ (javascript, ajax, php) 🎯 practice tasks 1 open your browser's developer tools (f12), go to the network tab , and reload a webpage. observe the list of http requests and find one with a status code and one with a or . 2 find 3 websites that use https (padlock icon) and look up one that uses only http. what's different in the address bar? 3 break down the full url into its parts: protocol, domain, path, and query string. 4 open command prompt (windows) and type . this shows you dns resolving a domain name to an ip address in real time. 5 research and write a short answer: what is the difference between a web browser and a search engine ? (hint: google is a search engine that runs inside a browser.) 6 visit — the world's first website, still live today. describe what you see. ← back to home day 2: html basics →","day2":"🏠 home › day 2 — html basics 📅 day 02 · beginner html basics the building block of every webpage — elements, tags, attributes, and structure. 📄 📋 topics covered today what is html and why we use it html document structure (doctype, html, head, body) html elements and tags html attributes creating your first html page semantic vs. non-semantic elements 🧱 what is html? html stands for hypertext markup language . it is the standard language used to create and structure content on the web. html is not a programming language — it's a markup language , which means it uses special tags to describe the structure of a webpage. every webpage you visit is built using html as its foundation. css styles it, and javascript makes it interactive — but html provides the skeleton. 💡 remember: html = structure, css = style, javascript = behaviour. these three work together to create every modern website. 🏗️ html document structure every html file follows a standard structure. let's look at a complete, minimal html page: html 📋 copy 🖥 browser output hello, world! this is my first webpage. understanding each part <!doctype html> — tells the browser this is an html5 document <html> — the root element that wraps all content <head> — contains meta info, title, links to css (not visible) <title> — the text shown on the browser tab <body> — all visible content goes inside here 🏷️ html attributes attributes provide additional information about html elements. they are always placed inside the opening tag and follow the pattern . html — attributes 📋 copy 🏠ï¸ important: always include the attribute on images. it helps screen readers and is displayed if the image fails to load. 🎯 practice tasks 1 create a file called and write a complete html structure from memory. 2 add a heading, a paragraph, and change the page title to your name. 3 add an image using the tag with src and alt attributes. 4 view your html file in a browser and inspect the elements using f12 devtools. 5 research the difference between block-level and inline elements in html. 6 list 5 semantic html5 elements (e.g. <header>, <footer>) and what each does. ← day 1: www day 3: text formatting →","day3":"🏠 home › day 3 — text formatting 📅 day 03 · beginner text formatting in html headings, paragraphs, bold, italic, underline and semantic text elements. ✏️ 📋 topics covered today html headings — h1 through h6 paragraphs and line breaks bold, italic, underline formatting semantic text elements (strong, em) superscript, subscript, and strikethrough quotations and preformatted text horizontal rules and special characters 🔠 html headings html provides six levels of headings, from (most important) to (least important). use headings to create a clear content hierarchy on your page. html — headings 📋 copy 🖥 browser output heading 1 — main title heading 2 — section title heading 3 — sub-section heading 4 — minor section heading 5 — small note heading 6 — smallest ✅ best practice: each page should have only one tag — it represents the main topic of the page. use h2-h6 for subsections. ✨ text formatting tags html has many tags for formatting text. some are visual (how text looks) and some are semantic (what the text means). html — text formatting 📋 copy 🖥 browser output bold text · important text · italic text · emphasized underlined · strikethrough · e = mc 2 · h 2 o use the function. 💬 quotations and preformatted text html — quotes & pre 📋 copy 🎯 practice tasks 1 create a page with all 6 heading levels and observe how they look in the browser. 2 write a paragraph about your favourite hobby using at least 3 formatting tags (bold, italic, underline). 3 add a blockquote with your favourite quote and credit the author. 4 write a chemical formula using subscript: co 2 , h 2 so 4 . 5 research: what's the difference between <b> and <strong>? why does it matter? 6 try <abbr>, <mark>, and <kbd> tags — what do they look like? 7 build a small \"profile card\" in html using text formatting tags. ← day 2: html basics day 4: lists & links →","day4":"🏠 home › day 4 — lists and links 📅 day 04 · beginner lists and links organize content with lists and connect pages using hyperlinks. 🔗 📋 topics covered today unordered lists (ul, li) ordered lists (ol, li) description lists (dl, dt, dd) nested lists hyperlinks (anchor tags) linking within a page using id anchors 📌 types of lists in html html provides three types of lists to organize content: unordered , ordered , and description lists. html — lists 📋 copy 🖥 browser output html css javascript learn html study css master javascript 🔗 html links (anchor tags) links are created using the (anchor) tag. the attribute specifies the destination url. html — anchor tags 📋 copy the target attribute — opens link in a new tab — opens in the same tab (default) — opens in the parent frame — opens in the full window ✅ security tip: when using , always add to prevent security vulnerabilities. 🎯 practice tasks 1 create a shopping list using an unordered list with at least 5 items. 2 create a \"top 5 steps to learn html\" ordered list. 3 build a navigation menu using an unordered list of anchor links. 4 create a page with \"jump to section\" links that scroll to headings using ids. 5 make a description list glossary with 5 web development terms. 6 build a 2-page mini website where page 1 links to page 2 and back. ← day 3: text formatting day 5: tables →","day5":"🏠 home › day 5 — tables 📅 day 05 · intermediate html tables structure data with rows, columns, headers, and cell merging in html. 📊 📋 topics covered today basic table structure (table, tr, td, th) table headers and captions table sections: thead, tbody, tfoot merging cells with colspan and rowspan styling tables with css 🗃️ creating a basic table html tables are used to display data in a grid of rows and columns. the key elements are: — the container for the entire table — table row — table header cell (bold, centered by default) — table data cell (regular data) — a title for the table html — basic table 📋 copy 🖥 browser output student grade report name subject grade alice html a+ bob css b average a 🔀 merging cells — colspan and rowspan use to merge cells horizontally (across columns) and to merge cells vertically (across rows). html — colspan & rowspan 📋 copy 💡 note: tables should be used for tabular data , not for page layout. css grid and flexbox are the modern tools for page layout. 🎯 practice tasks 1 create a class timetable table with days of the week as columns and time slots as rows. 2 build a product comparison table with at least 4 products and 5 features. 3 practice using colspan to create a \"merged header\" row. 4 add a caption and use thead, tbody, tfoot sections in your table. 5 style your table using css to add borders, alternating row colors, and hover effects. ← day 4: lists & links day 6: forms →","day6":"🏠 home › day 6 — forms 📅 day 06 · intermediate html forms collect user input — text fields, dropdowns, checkboxes, radio buttons, and form submission. 📝 📋 topics covered today the <form> element — action and method attributes text, email, password, number input types radio buttons and checkboxes dropdown menus (select) textarea for multi-line input labels, fieldsets, and legends submit and reset buttons 🏗️ form structure & input types the element is the container for all form controls. the attribute specifies where to send the data, and specifies how to send it ( or ). html — form & inputs 📋 copy 🖥 live demo form username email favourite topic html css javascript select course html css javascript message i agree to the terms submit form ⌨️ common input types — single-line text input — email with built-in validation — masked password field — numeric input with arrows — date picker — multi-select toggle — single choice from a group — file upload chooser — slider control — color picker — hidden data field / — action buttons 🏠ï¸ important: always use a for every input. the attribute on the label should match the on the input for accessibility. 🎯 practice tasks 1 build a complete registration form with: name, email, password, date of birth, and gender fields. 2 create a contact us form with a name, email, subject dropdown, and message textarea. 3 build a quiz form using radio buttons — 3 questions, each with 4 options. 4 add html5 form validation (required, minlength, pattern) to your registration form. 5 experiment with and input types. 6 use a and to group related form fields. 7 research the difference between get and post form methods. ← day 5: tables day 7: images & iframes →","day7":"🏠 home › day 7 — images, iframes and layout elements 📅 day 07 · intermediate images, iframes and layout elements embed images, external content, group form fields, and structure pages using layout containers. 🖼️ 📋 topics covered today <img> — displaying images on a webpage <iframe> — embedding external pages and content <fieldset> — grouping related form elements <div> — block-level container for layout and grouping 🖼️ the <img> tag the tag embeds an image on a webpage. it is a self-closing (void) element — no closing tag needed. src — path or url of the image alt — description for accessibility and fallback text width / height — size in pixels or percent title — tooltip on hover html — <img> 📋 copy 💡 formats: use for photos, for transparency, for icons, and for best compression. 📺 the <iframe> tag the (inline frame) tag embeds another html page or external content — such as a youtube video, google map, or external website — directly inside your page. html — <iframe> 📋 copy common attributes — url of the content to embed — size of the frame — accessibility description (required) — hides the border — enables fullscreen for videos ⚠️ note: some websites block embedding via . if a site doesn't appear in an iframe, it has disabled embedding. 🗂️ the <fieldset> tag the tag groups related form fields together inside a visible box. the tag gives the group a caption. html — <fieldset> 📋 copy 📦 the <div> tag — layout container the (division) is a generic block-level container used to group elements for styling and layout. it has no visual appearance on its own — you apply css to make it useful. it is one of the most widely used html elements. html — <div> layout 📋 copy 💡 semantic alternatives: prefer , , , over wherever the meaning applies — better for accessibility and seo. 🎯 practice tasks 1 add 3 images: one from a local file, one from a url, and one wrapped in a link. 2 embed a youtube video of your choice using . 3 embed a google map of your city using the google maps iframe embed code. 4 create a registration form using to group personal info and course info sections. 5 build a simple page layout using for header, nav, content, and footer — each with a different background color. 6 research: what is the difference between and ? ← day 6: html forms day 8: frames & layout →","day8":"🏠 home › day 8 — frames and layout design 📅 day 08 · intermediate frames and layout design understand how html frames divided browser windows historically, and how modern layout design evolved from that concept. 🪟 📋 topics covered today what are html frames and the <frameset> tag the <frame> tag and its attributes classic frame-based layout structure header, navigation, content, and status frames inline frames (<iframe>) as the modern alternative 🔲 what are html frames? in the early days of the web, html frames were used to divide a browser window into multiple independent sections. each section (frame) could load a separate html file. this allowed navigation menus to stay fixed while only the content area changed. frames were introduced in html 4.0 using the tag. however, frames are deprecated in html5 — modern web development uses css grid, flexbox, and iframes for similar results. ⚠️ deprecated: the and tags were removed in html5. they are covered here for historical understanding. use css layout and <iframe> for modern projects. key frame tags — replaces ; defines the frame grid using rows and columns — defines an individual frame and links it to an html file via — fallback content for browsers that don't support frames — inline frame embedded inside normal page body (still valid in html5) 🪟 classic frame-based layout a typical frame-based layout divided the browser window into four zones: header frame — top area with site logo and title (remained fixed) left/navigation frame — sidebar with links; clicking a link changed only the content frame right/content frame — main area where actual page content loaded status frame — bottom bar showing status, copyright, or notifications 🏠 header frame — site title & logo 🔗 left frame home about contact 📄 right / content frame main page content loads here 📊 status frame — footer / copyright visual representation of a classic frame-based browser layout 💻 frameset code example a frameset layout requires a main index file (which uses instead of ) and separate html files for each frame. html — index.html (main frameset) 📋 copy html — nav.html (navigation frame with target) 📋 copy key frame attributes — html file to load in the frame — identifier used by links' attribute to direct page loads — controls scrollbar behaviour — prevents user from resizing the frame border on — defines the grid in pixels, percent, or (remaining space) 🚀 modern alternative — css layout since is deprecated in html5, the same multi-section layouts are built today using css grid or flexbox . css — modern grid layout (replaces frameset) 📋 copy 🎓 historical perspective: frames taught an important idea — separate navigation from content. modern single-page apps (spas) achieve this elegantly with javascript routing, while css grid handles the visual layout. 🎯 practice tasks 1 create a classic frameset with 4 separate html files — header.html, nav.html, content.html, status.html — and an index.html linking them. 2 in nav.html, add three links that each load a different html page inside the frame using . 3 in the header frame, add a site logo image and a site name heading. 4 in the status frame, add a copyright notice and the current year. 5 recreate the same 4-section layout using css grid (header, nav, content, status) in a single html file — no frames required. 6 research: why were frames deprecated? list at least 3 disadvantages of html frames. ← day 7: images & iframes day 9: introduction to css →","day9":"🏠 home › day 9 — introduction to css 📅 day 09 · beginner introduction to css learn how cascading style sheets control the look, feel, and layout of every webpage you visit. 🎨 📋 topics covered today what is css? why css is used css syntax — selector, property, value inline css internal css external css 💅 what is css? css (cascading style sheets) is the language used to style and design webpages. while html provides the structure and content of a page, css controls how that content looks — its colors, fonts, sizes, spacing, and overall layout. without css, every webpage would look like a plain, unstyled document with black text on a white background. 💡 the three pillars: html = structure, css = presentation, javascript = behaviour. all three work together to create modern, interactive websites. why css is used control colors , fonts , and text sizes define spacing (margins and padding) around elements create layouts — multi-column pages, sidebars, grids add animations and transitions make pages responsive across different screen sizes separate design from content for easier maintenance 📐 css syntax a css rule is made up of a selector and a declaration block . the declaration block contains one or more property-value pairs. css — basic syntax 📋 copy selector — the html element(s) to style (e.g. , , ) property — the style aspect to change (e.g. , ) value — the setting to apply (e.g. , ) 🗂️ types of css there are three ways to add css to an html page, each suitable for different situations. 1. inline css applied directly inside an html tag using the attribute. affects only that single element. html — inline css 📋 copy 2. internal css written inside a tag within the section. applies to the whole page. html — internal css 📋 copy 3. external css written in a separate file and linked to the html page. best practice for real projects — one stylesheet can style many pages. html — linking external css 📋 copy ✅ priority order: inline css overrides internal css which overrides external css. inline styles have the highest specificity . 💻 practical 6 — resume using inline css create a simple personal resume (cv) webpage and style it entirely using inline css on each element. apply text color, font size, alignment, and background color. html — resume with inline css 📋 copy 🎯 practice tasks 1 create a resume using only inline css — style the name, job title, and sections with color, font-size, and text-align. 2 convert the same resume to use internal css inside a block. 3 move all the css into a separate file and link it using . 4 research: what does \"cascading\" mean in cascading style sheets? 5 experiment: apply conflicting styles using all three css types and observe which one wins. ← day 8: frames & layout day 10: css selectors →","day10":"🏠 home › day 10 — css selectors 📅 day 10 · beginner css selectors learn how to target html elements precisely using element, class, id, and group selectors. 🎯 📋 topics covered today element selector — target by tag name class selector — target by class attribute id selector — target a unique element by id group selector — apply the same style to multiple selectors 🎯 css selectors explained a css selector defines which html elements a css rule applies to. choosing the right selector gives you precise control over your styling. 1. element selector targets all html elements of a specific tag type. applies the style to every matching tag on the page. css — element selector 📋 copy 2. class selector targets elements that have a specific attribute. multiple elements can share the same class. uses a dot prefix ( ). css + html — class selector 📋 copy 3. id selector targets a single, unique element using its attribute. an id must be unique per page. uses a hash prefix ( ). css + html — id selector 📋 copy 4. group selector applies the same styles to multiple selectors at once, separated by commas. reduces code repetition. css — group selector 📋 copy ⚡ specificity ranking: id selectors (highest) > class selectors > element selectors (lowest). when rules conflict, the most specific one wins. 📌 quick reference css — all four selectors 📋 copy 💻 practical 5 — super market page using internal css create a supermarket webpage that organises products into departments. style it using internal css with class and id selectors. html — super market page (internal css) 📋 copy 🎯 practice tasks 1 create a webpage with at least 3 different element selectors styling headings and paragraphs. 2 create two different css classes ( and ) and apply them to different elements. 3 add a unique id to your page header and style it with a coloured background and white text. 4 use a group selector to give , , and the same font-family. 5 build the freshmart supermarket page with at least 3 product departments (vegetables, fruits, dairy). ← day 9: introduction to css day 11: css styling →","day11":"🏠 home › day 11 — css styling 📅 day 11 · beginner css styling control text appearance, fonts, colors, and backgrounds to bring your webpages to life. 🌈 📋 topics covered today text properties — align, decoration, transform, spacing font properties — family, size, weight, style color — named, hex, rgb, rgba, hsl background — color, image, repeat, size 📝 text properties text properties control alignment, decoration, transformation, and spacing of text. css — text properties 📋 copy 🖥 live demo centered, underlined, uppercase text this paragraph has a larger line-height for better readability. 🔤 font properties font properties define which typeface is used and how it is displayed. css — font properties 📋 copy 🎨 color css supports several color formats — use whichever is most convenient for your workflow. css — color formats 📋 copy 🖼️ background the background properties control what appears behind an element's content. css — background 📋 copy 💻 practical — improve super market page styling enhance the freshmart supermarket page from day 10 with the css styling techniques learned today: add to the entire page via the selector apply to department headings replace the solid header background with a style prices with a bold, contrasting color set on the store name add a subtle to the body 🎯 practice tasks 1 style a heading with uppercase, letter-spacing, and a colored underline. 2 create a card with a gradient background, white text, and rounded corners. 3 demonstrate all 4 color formats in a single stylesheet. 4 add a background image to a section and use . 5 enhance the day 10 supermarket page with better fonts, colors, and text styling. ← day 10: css selectors day 12: external css →","day12":"🏠 home › day 12 — external css 📅 day 12 · intermediate external css write styles in a separate file and apply them to multiple pages — the professional way to build websites. 🔗 📋 topics covered today what is external css? creating a file linking css to html using css reusability across multiple pages benefits — maintainability, consistency, code reuse 📄 what is external css? external css means writing all your styles in a separate file with the extension, then linking that file to one or more html pages. this is the industry-standard approach for any real project. why use external css? ✅ maintainability — change the style once; it updates every linked page automatically ✅ consistency — all pages share the exact same styles, ensuring a unified look ✅ code reuse — one stylesheet can serve hundreds of html pages ✅ separation of concerns — html handles structure, css handles design ✅ performance — browsers cache the css file, reducing load times on repeat visits 💡 best practice: for any project with more than one html file, always use external css. inline and internal css should only be used for quick tests or page-specific overrides. 🗂️ file structure a typical project using external css organises files like this: project folder structure 📋 copy 🔗 linking css to html add a tag inside the section of every html file that should use the stylesheet. html — linking external css 📋 copy the <link> tag attributes — tells the browser this is a stylesheet relationship — path to the css file (relative or absolute) style.css — example external stylesheet 📋 copy 💻 practical 7 — time table using external css create a class or college time table as an html page and style it using a separate external css file. create with the table structure create with all the styling rules link the css file using in the html head style the header row with a bold background color add alternating row colors using style free/lunch periods with a highlighted color timetable.html — starter structure 📋 copy 🎯 practice tasks 1 create a file and link it to 3 different html pages — confirm the same style applies to all. 2 build the time table page with an external css file for all styling. 3 refactor your day 10 supermarket page to use an external css file instead of internal css. 4 create a simple two-page mini-website (home + about) sharing one external stylesheet. 5 research: what is the difference between and attributes? ← day 11: css styling day 13: responsive design →","day13":"🏠 home › day 13 — responsive design and navbar 📅 day 13 · intermediate responsive design and navbar build webpages that adapt to any screen size, and create a professional navigation bar for your site. 📱 📋 topics covered today responsive web design — what it means and why it matters the viewport meta tag css media queries — adapting layout to screen size as a layout container navbar design — structure and styling 📱 responsive web design responsive web design (rwd) means building webpages that automatically adapt their layout and appearance to fit any screen size — whether viewed on a mobile phone, tablet, or desktop monitor. why is responsive design important? over 60% of web traffic comes from mobile devices a responsive site provides a good experience on every device google ranks mobile-friendly websites higher in search results step 1 — the viewport meta tag always add this to your — it tells the browser how to control the page dimensions on mobile devices. html — viewport meta tag 📋 copy step 2 — css media queries media queries apply different css rules depending on the screen width. this is the core technique of responsive design. css — media queries 📋 copy 💡 mobile first: a popular modern approach is to write styles for mobile first, then use media queries to add styles for larger screens. this keeps the base css lean. 📦 <div> as a layout container the (division) element is the most versatile layout tool in html. it is a block-level container with no visual styling of its own — you apply css to make it a header, card, column, or any other component. in responsive design, elements are grouped and rearranged using flexbox or grid to change from a multi-column desktop layout to a single-column mobile layout. html + css — responsive div columns 📋 copy 🧭 navbar design a navigation bar (navbar) is placed at the top of a webpage and contains links to different pages or sections. it is one of the most important ui components on any website. html + css — navbar 📋 copy 💻 practical 8 — college web page using all css types build a college website that demonstrates all three css types — inline, internal, and external. the page should include: 🧭 navbar — college name logo and navigation links (home, about, courses, contact) 🏷️ hero/header section — styled with external css, gradient background 📚 courses section — three course cards using a responsive flex layout 📞 contact section — name, email, phone 🔻 footer — copyright info 📱 responsive — cards stack vertically on small screens 📂 create + . use external css for main layout, internal css for page-specific tweaks, and inline css for individual element overrides. 🎯 practice tasks 1 add a viewport meta tag to all your previous html practicals. 2 create a 3-column div layout and use a media query to make it single-column on screens narrower than 600px. 3 build a navbar with a brand logo on the left and navigation links on the right, including hover effects. 4 build the complete college webpage using all three css types (inline, internal, external). 5 test your college page by resizing the browser window — ensure it is usable on mobile widths. 6 research: what is flexbox, and how does it help build responsive layouts? ← day 12: external css day 14: bootstrap introduction →","day14":"🏠 home › day 14 — bootstrap introduction 📅 day 14 · intermediate bootstrap introduction speed up your web development with bootstrap — the world's most popular front-end framework for building responsive, mobile-first websites. ⚡ 📋 topics covered today what is bootstrap? downloading bootstrap vs. using cdn bootstrap grid system — container, row, col basic bootstrap utility classes 🅱️ what is bootstrap? bootstrap is a free, open-source front-end css framework originally developed by twitter. it provides a large collection of pre-written css classes, javascript components, and a responsive grid system that allows developers to build professional, mobile-friendly websites quickly — without writing everything from scratch. instead of manually writing css for every button, card, or layout, you simply add bootstrap class names to your html elements and they are instantly styled. key benefits of bootstrap ⚡ faster ui development — pre-built components save hours of styling work 📱 built-in responsive design — layouts automatically adapt to any screen size 🧩 pre-designed components — buttons, navbars, cards, modals, forms, and more 🌐 cross-browser consistency — looks the same across chrome, firefox, safari, edge 📚 extensive documentation — easy to learn with official examples and guides 💡 bootstrap vs. custom css: bootstrap is perfect for rapid prototyping and building standard uis. for highly customised designs, you may combine bootstrap with your own custom css. 🔗 including bootstrap — cdn vs. download there are two ways to add bootstrap to your html project. both produce the same result. method 1 — download bootstrap visit getbootstrap.com , download the compiled css and js files, and add them to your project folder. then link the files locally: html — linking bootstrap locally 📋 copy method 2 — cdn (recommended for learning) a cdn (content delivery network) lets you load bootstrap directly from the internet without downloading anything. simply paste the cdn link into your html . html — bootstrap 5 via cdn 📋 copy ✅ always include the viewport meta tag when using bootstrap — without it, responsive breakpoints won't work correctly on mobile devices. 🔲 bootstrap grid system bootstrap's grid system is based on a 12-column flexible layout . it uses three main classes to build page layouts: — a centred, fixed-width wrapper for your page content — a horizontal group of columns (uses flexbox internally) — a column inside a row; bootstrap automatically divides space equally html — bootstrap grid (3 equal columns) 📋 copy fixed-width column sizing you can also specify how many of the 12 columns an element should span using (where n adds up to 12): html — fixed column widths 📋 copy responsive breakpoints bootstrap's grid is responsive — columns automatically stack on small screens. use breakpoint infixes to control when columns appear side by side: html — responsive grid breakpoints 📋 copy 🧰 basic bootstrap classes bootstrap provides hundreds of utility classes that let you style elements directly in html without writing any custom css. here are the most commonly used ones: html — bootstrap utility classes in action 📋 copy quick reference table class effect centred, max-width page wrapper horizontal flex row for columns grid column (n = 1–12) styled button (primary, danger, etc.) centre-align text bootstrap blue background padding / margin (0–5 scale) apply display: flex 💻 practical 9 — mobile-friendly college website using bootstrap build a full college website layout using bootstrap 5. the page should be fully responsive and include a header, navbar, introduction, courses section, and footer. html — college website with bootstrap 5 📋 copy ⚡ mobile nav: the button automatically shows a hamburger menu on mobile screens when the bootstrap js bundle is included. click it to toggle the navigation links. 🎯 practice tasks 1 create a blank html file, add the bootstrap 5 cdn link, and verify it works by styling a button with . 2 build a 3-column product card layout using bootstrap grid ( ). each card should have an image placeholder, title, and button. 3 create a responsive bootstrap navbar with a brand name and 4 navigation links. test it on a narrow window — the links should collapse into a hamburger menu. 4 build the complete college webpage from the practical above, then add a contact section with a bootstrap-styled form (name, email, message, submit button). 5 research: what is the difference between and in bootstrap? 6 experiment with bootstrap spacing utilities — try through and observe the differences. ← day 13: responsive design day 15: introduction to js →","day15":"🏠 home › day 15 — introduction to javascript 📅 day 15 · beginner introduction to javascript make your webpages interactive and dynamic. learn variables, data types, operators, arrays, and basic input/output methods. 💛 📋 topics covered today what is javascript and how does it work? how to add javascript to an html page variables — , , data types — string, number, boolean, null, undefined operators — arithmetic, comparison, logical arrays — collections of values output systems — , , , ⚡ what is javascript? javascript (js) is a lightweight, interpreted programming language that runs directly in the web browser. it was created in 1995 by brendan eich. while html provides structure and css handles styling, javascript is responsible for behaviour — making the page respond, change, and interact with the user. the three layers of a webpage: 🧱 html = structure (the bones of the page) 🎨 css = presentation (the skin and clothes) ⚡ javascript = behaviour (the muscles and brain) what can javascript do? validate form input before submission show/hide content without reloading the page fetch live data from a server (ajax) animate elements and create interactive effects build full web applications (react, angular, vue) run server-side code with node.js 💡 javascript is not java! despite similar names, they are completely different languages. java is a compiled, strongly-typed language used for desktop/android apps. javascript is an interpreted scripting language built for the web. 📎 how to add javascript to html there are three ways to include javascript in an html document. 1. inline javascript written directly inside an html event attribute. not recommended for large code. html — inline js 📋 copy 2. internal javascript (using <script> tag) a block placed inside the html file, typically just before the closing tag. html — internal script 📋 copy 3. external javascript (recommended) javascript code in a separate file, linked using the attribute. best for maintainability and reusability. html — external script 📋 copy 📦 variables — storing data a variable is a named container used to store a piece of data. javascript has three keywords to declare variables: — old way (function-scoped, can be re-declared). avoid using it. — modern way (block-scoped, can be reassigned). use for values that change. — modern way (block-scoped, cannot be reassigned). use for values that stay fixed. javascript — variables 📋 copy 🔣 data types javascript is a dynamically typed language — you don't need to specify what type of data a variable holds. javascript — data types 📋 copy ➕ operators arithmetic operators javascript — arithmetic operators 📋 copy comparison operators javascript — comparison operators 📋 copy 💡 always use instead of in your code. the triple equals checks both value and type, preventing many common bugs. for example, is but is . 🗂️ arrays an array is a special variable that can hold more than one value at a time. it stores an ordered list of items inside square brackets . array indexing starts at 0 , not 1. javascript — arrays 📋 copy 🖥️ output systems javascript provides multiple ways to display output or communicate with the user. javascript — all output methods 📋 copy quick comparison table: method use case show a simple popup message to the user debugging — visible only in browser devtools (f12) collect a short text input from the user write content to the page (mostly for testing) update content inside a specific html element 💻 practical — simple javascript examples create an html file with a block just before . complete each task: 1 declare variables for your name, age, and whether you are a student (boolean). log all three to the console using . 2 create an array of 5 subjects you study. print the first and last elements using array indexing. 3 use to greet the user when the page loads. 4 use to ask the user for their age, then use to display it back to them. 5 add items to your subject array using and print the updated array and its . 6 research: what is in javascript? what makes it appear? ← day 14: bootstrap day 16: functions & events →","day16":"🏠 home › day 16 — javascript functions and events 📅 day 16 · beginner js functions and events structure your code with reusable functions, respond to user actions with events, and start manipulating the dom dynamically. 🛠️ 📋 topics covered today functions — declaring and calling function parameters and arguments return values arrow functions (modern syntax) conditional statements — html events — onclick, onmouseover, onkeyup, and more dom — document object model introduction selecting and modifying html elements with js ⚙️ functions a function is a reusable block of code designed to perform a specific task. instead of writing the same code repeatedly, you write it once in a function and \"call\" it whenever you need it. defining and calling a function javascript — basic function 📋 copy functions with parameters a parameter is a placeholder variable listed inside the brackets when defining a function. an argument is the actual value you pass in when calling it. javascript — parameters & arguments 📋 copy return values a function can use the keyword to send a value back to wherever it was called from. this allows functions to calculate something and pass the result back. javascript — return values 📋 copy arrow functions (modern es6 syntax) arrow functions are a shorter, modern way to write functions. they use instead of the keyword. javascript — arrow functions 📋 copy 🔀 conditional statements conditional statements allow your program to make decisions and execute different code depending on whether a condition is or . javascript — if / else if / else 📋 copy 🖱️ html events events are actions or occurrences that happen in the browser, usually triggered by the user. javascript can respond to these events and run specific code when they occur. common html events: event triggered when… user clicks a button or element mouse pointer moves over an element mouse pointer moves away from an element the value of an input field changes user releases a key on the keyboard page (or image) has fully loaded form is submitted example — events in action html + js — multiple events demo 📋 copy 🌲 dom — document object model when a browser loads an html page, it creates a dom (document object model) — a tree-like representation of every element in the document. javascript uses the dom to access, change, add, or remove html elements and their styles dynamically without reloading the page. how the dom tree looks: dom tree structure 📋 copy selecting elements javascript — dom selection methods 📋 copy modifying elements javascript — dom manipulation 📋 copy 💡 innerhtml vs textcontent: use when you want to insert html tags (like ). use when you only want plain text — it's safer as it prevents html injection attacks. 💻 practical 10 — javascript program using 5 events build a single html page that demonstrates at least 5 different javascript events. each event should produce a visible result on the page (not just an alert). 1 add a button that uses to change the background colour of a using . 2 create a box that changes colour on and resets on . 3 create a text input with that displays everything the user types inside a element in real-time. 4 create a dropdown that uses to update a paragraph showing which option was selected. 5 write a function that validates that a name input is not empty when a button is clicked. if empty, display an error message in red. 6 bonus: use (instead of ) for at least one of the dom selections above. ← day 15: introduction to js day 17: js objects →","day17":"🏠 home › day 17 — javascript objects 📅 day 17 · intermediate javascript objects & loops master loops, built-in objects like date, string, and math, and use switch/case for clean multi-branch logic. 📅 📋 topics covered today loops — , , javascript objects — key-value pairs the date object — working with dates and time string handling — built-in string methods the math object — mathematical utilities switch case — clean multi-branch conditionals 🔁 loops loops run a block of code repeatedly, saving you from copy-pasting the same lines. 1. for loop — use when iterations are known javascript — for loop 📋 copy 2. while loop — use when iterations are unknown javascript — while loop 📋 copy 3. for...of — cleanest way to loop arrays javascript — for...of 📋 copy ⚠️ avoid infinite loops! always make sure your loop condition eventually becomes . forgetting will freeze the browser. 📦 javascript objects an object stores data as key: value pairs inside curly braces . unlike arrays (numbered indexes), objects use named keys — ideal for representing real-world things like a student or product. javascript — objects 📋 copy ⏰ the date object the built-in date object gives access to the current date and time from the user's system clock. javascript — date methods 📋 copy 🔤 string handling javascript strings have rich built-in methods for searching, modifying, and formatting text. javascript — string methods 📋 copy method description number of characters convert to all caps convert to all lowercase remove leading/trailing spaces returns true if text contains extract characters from index s to e replace first occurrence of a with b split into an array by separator 🔢 the math object the built-in math object provides mathematical constants and utility functions — no required. javascript — math object 📋 copy 🔀 switch case statement the statement evaluates one expression and runs the matching block. it is cleaner than long chains when comparing one variable against many fixed values. — compared against the switch expression — exits the block, prevents accidental fall-through — runs when no case matches (like ) javascript — switch case (day of week) 📋 copy javascript — switch with user input 📋 copy 💡 don't forget ! without it, javascript continues into the next case regardless of whether it matches — called fall-through . 💻 practicals 1 use to ask \"enter a number 1–7\". use to alert the day name. add a for invalid numbers. 2 display today's date on the webpage using the object and . 3 ask the user to type a sentence via . display it in uppercase, its character count, and whether it includes the word \"javascript\". 4 build a \"dice roller\" button — clicks generate a random integer from 1–6 and display it on screen. 5 create an array of 5 student names. loop through with and display each as an inside a using . ← day 16: functions & events day 18: form validation →","day18":"🏠 home › day 18 — form validation 📅 day 18 · intermediate form validation ensure clean, safe user input using html5 validation attributes, javascript validators, and regular expressions. ✅ 📋 topics covered today why form validation matters html5 validation attributes — , , , , client-side vs server-side validation javascript manual validation real-time validation with regular expressions (regex) — syntax and usage common regex patterns 🛡️ why form validation matters forms are the primary way users send information to a website. without validation, bad or malicious data can break your application or create serious security risks. data integrity: ensure all required fields are filled correctly before processing. user experience: provide instant, helpful feedback instead of a server error page. security: prevent common attacks like sql injection and cross-site scripting (xss) by sanitizing input. reduced server load: catch errors on the client before wasting a round-trip to the server. ⚠️ never trust client-side validation alone! a tech-savvy user can bypass html and javascript validation using browser devtools. always validate again on the server. client-side validation is for ux; server-side validation is for security. 📝 html5 built-in validation attributes html5 introduced validation attributes that work directly on elements without any javascript. the browser automatically checks these rules when a form is submitted. html — validation attributes 📋 copy common input types that add validation type attribute validates must be a valid email address format must be a numeric value must start with http:// or https:// shows date picker; must be a valid date phone number field (use with pattern for format) ⚙️ javascript manual validation html5 attributes cover simple cases, but for richer feedback (custom error messages, live checking, complex rules) you write validation logic in javascript. html + js — manual form validation 📋 copy real-time validation with js — live character counter 📋 copy 🔍 regular expressions (regex) a regular expression (regex) is a powerful pattern that describes a set of strings. in form validation, regex allows you to enforce precise rules — like \"must start with a letter\" or \"must contain exactly 10 digits\". regex syntax basics pattern meaning example match any uppercase letter a–z a, b, z any lowercase letter a–z a, m, z any digit 0–9 0, 5, 9 any digit (shorthand for [0-9]) 3, 7 any word character (letters, digits, _) a, 3, _ any character except newline a, !, 5 0 or more of the previous character \"\" or \"aaa\" 1 or more of the previous character \"a\", \"aaa\" 0 or 1 of the previous character (optional) \"\" or \"a\" exactly n repetitions = \"1234\" between m and n repetitions and start (^) and end ($) of the string using regex in html attribute html — pattern attribute 📋 copy using regex in javascript with javascript — regex .test() 📋 copy 🏗️ complete validated registration form this brings everything together — html5 attributes, javascript, and regex — into a single sign-up form. full example — validated registration form 📋 copy 💻 practical 12 — build a validated registration form 1 create a registration form with fields: full name, email, mobile number, password, and confirm password. 2 use html5 attributes ( , , ) for basic validation. 3 write a javascript function that uses regex to validate name (letters only), mobile (10 digits), and password (min 8 chars, 1 letter + 1 number). 4 show a red error message below each invalid field and a green ✅ for each valid field. 5 add a \"confirm password\" check — if the two password fields don't match, show an error. 6 bonus: add a live password strength indicator using that shows weak / medium / strong based on criteria (length, uppercase, numbers). ← day 17: js objects day 19: ajax →","day19":"🏠 home › day 19 — ajax 📅 day 19 · advanced ajax communicate with servers and update parts of a webpage dynamically without requiring a full page reload. 🔄 📋 topics covered today what is ajax? purpose of ajax advantages and disadvantages ajax web applications ⚡ what is ajax? ajax stands for asynchronous javascript and xml . it is not a programming language, but rather a technique used in web development that allows a webpage to communicate with a server in the background and update parts of the page without reloading the entire page. this technique helps create faster, smoother, and more interactive web applications. ajax commonly uses a combination of: javascript to manage the logic and requests. xml or json to format the data being transferred (json is much more common today). xmlhttprequest object (or the modern fetch api ) to exchange data with a web server asynchronously. html and css to display and style the updated data. 🎯 purpose of ajax ajax is used to dramatically improve user experience (ux) and build highly responsive web applications. its main purposes include: loading data dynamically: requesting data from the server after the initial page has loaded. partial page updates: updating specific parts of a webpage without needing to refresh the entire window. background data submission: sending data (like form submissions) to the server smoothly in the background. common use cases: 🔍 live search suggestions (e.g., google auto-complete) 💬 loading comments or feed posts dynamically (e.g., infinite scrolling on social media) 🔄 auto-refreshing content (e.g., live sports scores or stock tickers) ⚖️ advantages & disadvantages ✅ advantages of ajax faster interaction: since only small amounts of data are transferred, applications feel much faster. no full page reloads: users aren't interrupted by a white screen while waiting for the next page to load. better user experience: apps behave more like fast desktop applications than traditional websites. reduced server load: the server only sends the requested data (like json), rather than sending entire html pages. ❌ disadvantages of ajax code complexity: handling asynchronous javascript states, callbacks, or promises can be complex. debugging difficulty: because the url doesn't change and actions happen in the background, bugs can be harder to track. browser compatibility: very old browsers handle xmlhttprequest differently, requiring polyfills (though this is rare today). seo challenges: historically, search engines struggled to index content loaded dynamically via ajax (though modern crawlers are much better at this). 🌐 ajax web applications many modern websites rely heavily on ajax to provide a rich, dynamic experience. some of the most famous examples include: 📧 gmail: loads emails dynamically and sends messages entirely in the background. 🗺️ google maps: drags and updates map tiles smoothly without reloading the page. 💬 online chat applications: delivers and sends instant messages in real-time. 🔔 live notifications: facebook and twitter alert bells use ajax to poll for new activity. 💻 example ajax code (xmlhttprequest) here is a basic example showing how to retrieve data from a text file on a server using the classic object. javascript — ajax request 📋 copy html — using the ajax function 📋 copy 🛠️ practical 4 — retrieve data from text file using ajax practice writing your first ajax request by loading simple text into your webpage asynchronously. 1 create a simple text file called in the same folder as your html file, and add a welcoming sentence inside it. 2 create an html webpage containing a and an empty element. 3 write the javascript function utilizing the object, as shown in the example above. 4 test the application! clicking the button should display the content of inside the div, without the page refreshing. ⚠️ note: most modern browsers block ajax requests for local files (using the protocol) due to security restrictions (cors). you may need to run this file through a local server (like the vs code live server extension) for it to work properly. ← day 18: form validation day 20: xml & json →","day20":"🏠 home › day 20 — xml & json 📅 day 20 · advanced xml & json master the two most important data formats used in modern web development — structured xml and lightweight json. 📦 📋 topics covered today xml introduction xml structure dtd (document type definition) xml schema xsl / xslt json basics json keys, values, arrays & objects 🏷️ xml introduction xml stands for extensible markup language . it is designed to store and transport data . unlike html (which focuses on how content is displayed), xml is all about describing what the data means . key features of xml: self-descriptive: tags are custom and named by the developer to describe their own data. platform independent: xml can be read and used across different operating systems, applications, and languages. human readable: the text-based, tag-wrapped format is easy for anyone to understand. strict syntax: every tag that is opened must be properly closed. 💡 html vs xml: html tells the browser how to display data. xml tells applications what the data is . html has predefined tags like and . in xml, you create your own tags. 🌳 xml structure every xml document has a tree-like structure, starting with a single root element that wraps all other elements. each element can contain child elements, attributes, and text data. xml — student record 📋 copy an xml document contains: root element — the outermost, single parent tag (e.g. ) child elements — nested inside the root (e.g. ) tags — opening and closing labels that wrap data data values — the actual content between the tags 📜 dtd (document type definition) a dtd defines the legal building blocks of an xml document. it sets the rules for the structure of the xml — which elements are allowed, how many can appear, and in what order — ensuring all xml files following it have a consistent format. xml — internal dtd example 📋 copy 🛡️ xml schema (xsd) xml schema (also called xsd — xml schema definition) is a more powerful and modern alternative to dtd. it is used to define: data types — e.g., specifying that must be an integer, not a string element structure — defining which child elements an element can contain validation rules — minimum/maximum values, allowed patterns, required fields ⚡ dtd vs xsd: dtd is simpler but limited. xml schema is verbose but much more precise — it supports data types, namespaces, and complex constraints. xsd is preferred in professional environments. 🎨 xsl / xslt xsl (extensible stylesheet language) is a family of languages used to work with xml documents. it has two main parts: xslt (xsl transformations) — used to transform xml into other formats such as html, plain text, or a different xml structure. xpath — a language for navigating through elements and attributes in an xml document (used inside xslt). how xslt works: you give xslt two files: an xml data file and an xsl template file . the xslt processor then merges them to produce a final output — typically an html page ready for the browser. xml — linking an xsl stylesheet 📋 copy ⚡ json basics json (javascript object notation) is a lightweight, text-based format for storing and exchanging structured data. it is the dominant format used today between web servers and client applications (apis). why json is popular: lightweight: minimal syntax — no bulky tags like xml. easy to read: closely resembles javascript objects, familiar and intuitive. easy to parse: javascript can natively convert json using . widely supported: every modern programming language has a json library. json — basic structure 📋 copy 🔩 json keys, values, arrays & objects 🔑 keys & values json data is written in key / value pairs . the key is always a string wrapped in double quotes. the value can be a string, number, boolean, array, object, or null. json — keys & values 📋 copy 📋 json arrays a json array is an ordered list of values enclosed in square brackets . it can hold strings, numbers, booleans, objects, or even other arrays. json — array example 📋 copy 📦 nested json objects a json value can itself be another json object — creating a nested object . this allows complex hierarchical data to be represented. json — nested object 📋 copy 💻 practical — create xml student information file create a well-structured xml file to store student data using proper xml syntax. 1 create a new file called . 2 add the xml declaration at the top: 3 create a root element and add at least 3 entries inside it. 4 each student should have: , , , and child elements. 5 open the file in a browser — a well-formed xml will display with the tree shown in its full structure. 💻 practical — transform xml using xsl write a basic xslt transformation to turn your xml student file into a readable html table page. 1 add the xsl stylesheet link to your using the processing instruction. 2 create a new file called . 3 in the xsl file, use to define how each should be displayed as an html table row. 4 open the xml file in a browser — the xslt will kick in and display your data as a formatted html table. 💻 practical — json → javascript object demonstrate converting json-formatted data into a javascript object and display it on a webpage. javascript — parse json and display data 📋 copy 1 create a json string for a student with name, course, and subjects (as an array). 2 use to convert it into a js object. 3 display the student name and subjects list inside a element on the webpage using . ← day 19: ajax 🏠 back to home"};
